We can also check our data to see if it has constant seasonal variance which means when the magnitude of the swings in our data is constant over time. from this graph, we can see that it do not appear to have a strong seasonal trend in our data. it also also appear that it do not have a constant variance so we prefer to do some transformation.

#1.c
library(tseries)
## Warning: package 'tseries' was built under R version 3.6.2
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'quantmod':
##   method            from
##   as.zoo.data.frame zoo
ts.plot(data$morg)

normalized=  data$morg/ max(data$morg)

acf(normalized,lag.max = length(data$morg),
         xlab = "lag #", ylab = 'ACF',main=' ')

adf.test(data$morg)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  data$morg
## Dickey-Fuller = -2.3071, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.4482
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
dif = diff(data$morg, lag= 7)
plot.ts(dif)

adf.test(dif)
## Warning in adf.test(dif): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  dif
## Dickey-Fuller = -4.3276, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

as we can see from this graph, we can see that this variance is varing due to the time. hence, this variance is not constant. so, this is nonstationary. besides, we also can see that from this test, we get the lag= 7, and the p value that we get is 0.4482, which is larger than 0.05. therefore, we do not have enough data to reject the null hypothesis, meaning that the time series for morg is nonstationary.
for transformation, since we calculate the difference, we can see that the p value we get from adf test for the difference less than 0.05. hence, we can see that we reject the null hypothesis that the data is stationary, not trend present.

acf(dif)

pacf(dif)

mod1 <- arima(data$morg, order = c(7,1,0), season = list( order = c(0,1,1), period=12))

for the acf graph, this means that its lag around 7, because it cut off around 7. then we can know that q= 7, and then we look for spikes at lags that are multiples of preview one, but we can see that S = 9, but then Q=1 since only have a spike at 9. and d= D = 0 since there have zero order differencing for seasonal and nonseasonal component. for pacf, we can see that there is one spike in low lags, hence p =1, and we do not see any spike around high value so that P=0.
